docs.abstract: “Student protesters were not violating Mr. Murray’s First Amendment rights when they spoke out against him. They were changing the terms of the discussion.”
docs.snippet: “Student protesters were not violating Mr. Murray’s First Amendment rights when they spoke out against him. They were changing the terms of the discussion.”
docs.lead_paragraph: Last week, a guest lecture at Middlebury College by   Charles Murray, a scholar at the American Enterprise Institute, was disrupted by hundreds of student protesters.  Allison Stanger, a political science professor at the college, subsequently interviewed Mr. Murray at an alternate location on campus. As they left the second venue, they were violently confronted by masked protesters, and Ms. Stanger was injured. On Campus  reached out to several students to reflect on the event.

headline.main: Discord at Middlebury: Students on the Anti-Murray Protests

docs.abstract: Photos of the counselor to the president sitting casually on a couch in the Oval Office were all the kindling needed to ignite into a battle over decorum.
docs.snippet: Photos of the counselor to the president sitting casually on a couch in the Oval Office were all the kindling needed to ignite into a battle over decorum.
docs.lead_paragraph: During President Trump’s meeting with dozens of leaders of historically black universities on Monday, Kellyanne Conway, the White House counselor, made herself at home in the Oval Office. She hopped onto a couch, sat back on her heels and tapped on her phone.

headline.main: Kellyanne Conway Casually Sits, and Etiquette Arbiters Take a Stand
